The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Enchanting act

 Designed as a comic fantasy, Operation Bhomragarh makes a strong, serious comment on the abuse and misappropriation of public funds by the state. Satirical to the core, it also exposes how peoples rights are endangered and violated to indulge the ruling classs outrageous whims and caprices. When Alhadi, the pet white elephant of King Bhramarchandra of Bhomragarh, is kidnapped by Brindaban, a jungle bandit, the bankrupt king asks his subjects to pay the ransom for its release. They, however, refuse to help their unworthy king. Meanwhile, the Rajabahadur of Mayurhati sees in the situation a chance to fulfil his mission of ridding the world of its terrorists. Equipped with sophisticated, modern weapons, he arrives, only to bring more disaster and calamity to an already beleaguered people. Finally, Bhenpu, a young snake charmer, saves the day for Bhomragarh, his enchanted flute bringing an end to Brindaban and to the evil designs of the emperor of Mayurhati. Drama, direction and acting: Manoj Mitra.

 Event: Play in Bengali, Operation Bhomragarh, produced by Sundaram

 When: Today at 3 pm and 6.30 pm

 Where: Academy of Fine Arts




